---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../../components/nav/SiteHeader.astro';
import { DOCS_URL, DOCSRS_BASE } from '../../consts';
---
<BaseLayout
  title="Documentation — DeepCausality"
  description="What DeepCausality is, what dynamic causality does differently from classical causal frameworks, and when to reach for it, with a link to the full documentation."
>
  <SiteHeader />
  <article class="overview">
    <header class="overview-head">
      <p class="eyebrow">Documentation</p>
      <h1>What is DeepCausality?</h1>
    </header>
    <div class="overview-prose">
      <p>
        DeepCausality is an open-source Rust framework for computational causality. It targets advanced
        systems where time is not linear, causal rules can change, and the context evolves at runtime. It
        is the reference implementation of the <em>Effect Propagation Process</em> (EPP), which rests on a single axiom: every effect is derived from a prior effect by a causal function
        (<code>m₂ = m₁ &gt;&gt;= f</code>).
      </p>
      <p>
        Classical computational causality assumes a fixed background spacetime and a static causal
        structure. Pearl&rsquo;s structural causal models, Granger causality, dynamic Bayesian networks,
        and the Rubin model all share that assumption. It holds for static systems, but it breaks for
        dynamic systems such as a drone that loses GPS inside a tunnel, where the rules and the
        context are themselves dynamic. Dynamic causality treats causality as a process that is independent of a fixed
        spacetime. DeepCausality makes that idea first-class:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>
          <strong>One carrier.</strong> The <em>propagating effect</em> folds causal
          input (evidence) and output (effect) into a single isomorphic type, so one step&rsquo;s output
          is directly the next step&rsquo;s input. It reasons deterministically or probabilistically. It
          is either stateless (<code>PropagatingEffect</code>) or stateful, carrying Markovian state and
          context (<code>PropagatingProcess</code>). Monadic <code>bind</code> sequences it, Pearl&rsquo;s
          <code>intervene</code>/<code>do()</code> rewrites a value mid-chain for counterfactuals, and a
          deterministic audit log accrues by construction.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>One causal unit.</strong> The <em>Causaloid</em> folds cause and effect into a single
          isomorphic-recursive type. Without temporal order, there is no way to tell a cause from its
          effect, so it drops the split and merges them into one entity: a causal function that takes a
          propagating effect and returns one. In its base form, the Singleton, it wraps a single such
          function. A Collection groups several Causaloids under an aggregate rule (all, any, none, or
          k-of-n). A Graph wires them into a hypergraph. All three are the same type, so one node can
          stand for a single mechanism or an entire sub-model.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Four reasoning modalities under one type:</strong> static, dynamic, adaptive, and
          emergent. You pick the one that fits your problem.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>From inference to action: the Causal State Machine.</strong> It turns a reasoning
          verdict into an action. A finite state machine needs every state enumerated at design time; the
          CSM instead treats a state as an inferred predicate, so it fires the right action for
          situations no one enumerated up front.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>A programmable safety layer, the <em>Effect Ethos</em>.</strong> It checks every
          CSM-proposed action against an immutable set of computable norms before that action executes.
          The trail stays auditable and deterministic even when the reasoning itself is dynamic.
        </li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        This matters most in high-stakes domains: medicine, finance, robotics, avionics, and
        industrial control. A regulator, an operator, or a courtroom will ask why a decision was made,
        and a deterministic audit trail answers that question. It also fits whenever classical tooling
        forces you to stitch two or three libraries together. Dynamic control loops. Multi-physics
        simulations that cross regimes mid-pipeline. Financial systems facing regime change. When a
        system grows complex and dynamic, reach for DeepCausality.
      </p>
      <p class="overview-cta">
        <a class="overview-btn" href={DOCS_URL}>Read the full documentation <span aria-hidden="true">→</span></a>
      </p>
      <p class="overview-note">
        The exhaustive per-crate API reference lives on <a href={`${DOCSRS_BASE}/deep_causality`}>docs.rs</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </article>

  <style>
    .overview {
      max-width: var(--w-doc);
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: var(--space-7) var(--space-4) var(--space-9);
    }
    @media (min-width: 900px) {
      .overview { padding: var(--space-9) var(--space-5); }
    }
    .overview-head { margin-bottom: var(--space-6); }
    .overview-head .eyebrow {
      margin: 0 0 var(--space-2) 0;
      font-size: var(--t-eyebrow);
      letter-spacing: var(--ls-eyebrow);
      text-transform: uppercase;
      color: var(--fg-2);
    }
    .overview-head h1 { margin: 0; }
    .overview-prose { max-width: var(--w-prose); }
    .overview-prose p,
    .overview-prose li { color: var(--fg-1); }
    .overview-prose p { max-width: var(--measure); margin: 0 0 var(--space-4) 0; }
    .overview-prose strong { color: var(--fg-0); }
    .overview-prose ul { padding-left: var(--space-5); margin: 0 0 var(--space-4) 0; }
    .overview-prose li { margin: var(--space-2) 0; max-width: var(--measure); }
    .overview-prose a {
      text-decoration: underline;
      text-decoration-color: var(--line-2);
      text-underline-offset: 2px;
    }

    .overview-cta { margin: var(--space-6) 0 var(--space-5); }
    .overview-btn {
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: var(--space-2);
      height: 44px;
      padding: 0 var(--space-5);
      border-radius: var(--radius-sm);
      background: var(--accent);
      color: var(--accent-ink);
      border: 1px solid var(--accent);
      font-weight: 540;
      text-decoration: none;
      box-shadow: 0 1px 0 0 color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 60%, black) inset,
                  0 1px 2px 0 color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 50%, transparent);
      transition: background-color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out),
                  border-color var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out),
                  transform var(--dur-fast) var(--ease-out);
    }
    .overview-btn:hover {
      background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 90%, white);
      border-color: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 90%, white);
    }
    .overview-btn:active { transform: translateY(1px); }

    .overview-note { font-size: var(--t-body-sm); color: var(--fg-2); }
  </style>
</BaseLayout>
